{{Infobox holiday |holiday_name = Cassinga Day |type = National |image = |imagesize = |caption = |official_name = |nickname = |observedby = [[Namibia]] |litcolor = |longtype = |significance = |begins = |ends = |date = 4 May |scheduling = Same date each year |frequency = Annual |duration = 1 day}}
'''Cassinga Day''' is a national public holiday in [[Namibia]] remembering the [[Cassinga Massacre]]. Commemorated annually on [[4 May]], the date "remembers those (approximately 600)<ref>[http://www.namibian.com.na/index.php?id=29057 Let's Review Our National Holidays] in The Namibian, 27 April, 2007</ref> killed in 1978 when the [[South African Defence Force]] attacked a [[South West Africa People's Organization|SWAPO]] base at [[Cassinga]] in southern [[Angola]]".<ref>[http://www.thecommonwealth.org/YearbookInternal/138840/society/ The Commonwealth Yearbook] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927000000/http://www.thecommonwealth.org/YearbookInternal/138840/society/ |date=September 27, 2007 }}</ref> Commemorations are marked yearly by ceremonies at [[Heroes' Acre (Namibia)|Heroes' Acre]], outside of [[Windhoek]]. These ceremonies are attended by many important national political figures, including incumbent [[President of Namibia|President]] [[Hage Geingob]] and former [[List of Presidents of Namibia|President]]s [[Hifikepunye Pohamba]] and [[Sam Nujoma]] (as of 2016).<ref>[http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2006-09/21/content_5119906.htm Namibian national reconciliation policy] in Xinhua News Agency, 21 September, 2006.</ref>
==4 May 1978== In the morning of May 4, 1978, the South African Defence Force ran an air strike on camp ''Cassinga'' near the village of [[Cassinga]], followed by a deployment of [[paratroopers]]. The camp was inhabited by exiled SWAPO sympathisers and their families. 165 men, 294 women and 300 children died in this attack. Later the same day the nearby camp ''Vietnam'' in the village of Tchetequela was also attacked. {{As of|2016}} the graves are unmarked but the [[Government of Namibia|Namibian government]] plans to erect a memorial site.<ref>{{Cite news | title=Remembering Cassinga Day | last=Muraranganda | first=Elvis | newspaper=[[New Era (Namibia)|New Era]] | date=3 May 2016 | page=3 | url=https://www.newera.com.na/2016/05/03/remembering-cassinga-day/}}</ref>
